The dermis and underlying fascia are diffusely expanded by mild to severe fibrosis and a few mixed inflammatory cells with areas of mild to moderate edema. There is a focal area of more severe dermal inflammation involving lymphocytes, plasma cells, macrophages and a few neutrophils. This is associated with marked epidermal hyperplasia forming exophytic papillary fronds. There is extensive superficial epithelial degeneration, keratinocytes ballooning and necrosis, ulceration and subcorneal pustules. Parakeratotic hyperkeratosis and serocellular exudation are mild to moderate in the proliferative area. This is an interesting lesion of unknown etiology with severe ulceration and inflammation that obscures much of the mass-like area. I suspect that this may be either a viral papilloma or an epidermal hamartoma that has been traumatized with severe inflammation and fibrosis and with possible secondary infection. The surrounding and subjacent dermis and fascia have fibrosis and edema but mild inflammation suggesting a resolving secondary infection which is consistent with the partial response to antimicrobial therapy.
